iveness or multiculturalism in the Eastern European urban sphere, they offer insights into the history of metropolises like Prague, Baku, Moscow or St Petersburg, and regional centers like Lviv or Irkutsk.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 4aBaltikum. 4aEuropa. 4aGeschichtswissenschaft. 4aKaukasus. 4aKulturgeschichte. 4aOsteuropa. 4aOsteuropäische Geschichte. 4aRussland. 4aSozialgeschichte. 4aStadt. 4aUrban Studies. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aBaltics.  aCaucasus.  aCity.  aCultural History.  aEastern Europe.  aEastern European History.  aEurope.  aHistory.  aRussia.  aSocial History.  aUrban Studies.1 aAlbrecht, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlshanskaya, Alena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBicknell, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBicknell, Lisa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBogojavlenska, Svetlana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuchholz, Martin-Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConrad, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConrad, Benjamin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFriedl, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrings, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHensel-Grobe, Meike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJivazada, Elnura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManer, Hans-Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/